V'''Jay Frank Rosenberg''' (April 18, 1942 in [[Chicago]] IL \u2013 February 21, 2008 in [[Chapel Hill NC]]) was a Professor of Philosophy at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]. He was a  student of [[Wilfrid Sellars]] and established his reputation with ten books and over 80 articles in metaphysics, epistemology, the philosophy of language, and the history of philosophy (especially [[Immanuel Kant|Kant]]). His most commercially successful work, ''The Practice of Philosophy: A Handbook for Beginners'', is a standard text in introductory philosophy courses, and has been translated into German.\u000a\u000aRosenberg's first publication, ''The Impoverished Students' Book of Cookery, Drinkery, and Housekeepery!'', written while an undergraduate at [[Reed College]], has since been republished and is available from the Reed College bookstore.  Also while at Reed, Rosenberg was a keen observer and commenter of the tabletop game ''Empire'', though he never played.\u000a\u000aRosenberg won almost $50,000 on the television game show ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' in 1986 and returned for the program's [[Jeopardy! Ultimate Tournament of Champions|Ultimate Tournament of Champions]].\u000a\u000a==Books==\u000a* ''Readings in the Philosophy of Language'', co-edited with Charles Travis; Prentice-Hall, Inc.; Englewood Cliffs, NJ; 1971.\u000a* ''Linguistic Representation'', D. Reidel Publishing Co.; Dordrecht, Holland; 1974.\u000a** Pallas Paperback edition, 1978; · Second edition, 1981.\u000a* ''The Practice of Philosophy'', Prentice-Hall, Inc.; Englewood Cliffs, NJ; 1978\u000a** Second edition, revised and enlarged, 1984.\u000a** Third edition, newly revised and enlarged, Prentice-Hall, Inc.; Upper Saddle River, NJ; 1996.\u000a* ''One World and Our Knowledge of It'', D. Reidel Publishing Co.; Dordrecht, Holland; 1980.\u000a* ''Thinking Clearly About Death'', Prentice-Hall, Inc.; Englewood Cliffs, NJ.; 1983.\u000a** Second edition, revised and enlarged; Hackett Publishing Co.; Indianapolis, IN, and Cambridge, MA; 1998.\u000a* ''The Thinking Self'', Temple University Press; Philadelphia, PA; 1986.\u000a* ''Beyond Formalism: Naming and Necessity for Human Beings'', Temple University Press; Philadelphia, PA; 1994\u000a* ''Three Conversations About Knowing'', Hackett Publishing Co.; Indianapolis, IN, and Cambridge, MA; 2000\u000a* ''Thinking About Knowing'', Oxford University Press; Oxford; 2002\u000a* ''Accessing Kant'', Oxford University Press; Oxford: 2005\u000a* ''Wilfrid Sellars: Fusing the Images'', Oxford University Press; Oxford: 2007\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a* [[American philosophy]]\u000a* [[List of American philosophers]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{no footnotes|date=April 2008}}\u000a# http://leiterreports.typepad.com/blog/2008/02/in-memoriam-jay.html\u000a# http://www.legacy.com/NewsObserver/Obituaries.asp?Page=LifeStory&PersonID=104791474\u000a# http://philosophy.unc.edu/rberg.htm (Homepage at UNC) {{deadlink|date=January 2015}}\u000a# http://www.unc.edu/~jfr (Personal Homepage) {{deadlink|date=January 2015}}\u000a# http://www.unc.edu/%7Ejfr/CV4Web-070324.htm (CV) {{deadlink|date=January 2015}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenberg, Jay}}\u000a[[Category:1942 births]]\u000a[[Category:2008 deaths]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Jeopardy! contestants]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers|Rosenberg, Jay F.]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers|Rosenberg, Jay F.]]\u000a[[Category:Analytic philosophers|Rosenberg, Jay F.]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of language|Rosenberg, Jay F.]]\u000a[[Category:Metaphysicians|Rosenberg, Jay F.]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophy academics|Rosenberg, Jay F.]]\u000a[[Category:Reed College alumni]]\u000a[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill faculty|Rosenberg, Jay F.]]\u000a[[Category:American historians of philosophy]]\u000a[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]
